goals.question: What is the correlation between X and Y?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of X and Y
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify if there is any relationship between X and Y. If there is a positive correlation, then as X increases, Y also increases. If there is a negative correlation, then as X increases, Y decreases.

goals.question: What is the distribution of X?
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify the frequency distribution of X. It helps to identify if X is normally distributed or skewed.

goals.question: What is the distribution of Y?
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify the frequency distribution of Y. It helps to identify if Y is normally distributed or skewed.

goals.question: What is the trend of X over time?
goals.visualization: Line chart of X over time
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify the trend of X over time. It helps to identify if X is increasing, decreasing or staying constant over time.

goals.question: What is the relationship between X and Series?
goals.visualization: Box plot of X by Series
goals.rationale: This visualization helps to identify if there is any relationship between X and Series. It helps to identify if there are any outliers or differences in the distribution of X across different Series.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.scatterplot(data=data, x='X', y='Y')
    plt.title('What is the correlation between X and Y?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='X', kde=True, color='blue', bins=20)
    median_x = data['X'].median()
    plt.axvline(median_x, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f'Median: {median_x:.2f}')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of X?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

    sns.histplot(data=data, x='Y', kde=True, color='blue', label='Y Distribution')

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Series'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Series'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['Series'])]

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.lineplot(x='Series', y='X', data=data)
    plt.title('What is the trend of X over time?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Time')
    plt.ylabel('X')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title='X', loc='upper left')

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

chart = plot(data)
